## Required reading
- Official Bevy repo + examples (MIT OR Apache-2.0; Bevy Engine project) — https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy
- Headless renderer example (camera → GPU image → buffer → channel → PNG) — https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy/blob/main/examples/app/headless_renderer.rs
- Bevy docs (official) — https://bevy.org and https://docs.rs/bevy
- bevy-game-engine Claude skill — community, MIT, by Lauri Gates — https://github.com/laurigates/claude-plugins/blob/main/bevy-plugin/skills/bevy-game-engine/skill.md

## Render
```bash
# install Rust (macOS / Linux)
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh && source $HOME/.cargo/env

# run the OOTA-scaffolded project (headless: WinitPlugin disabled + ScheduleRunnerPlugin)
cargo run --release    # writes out/000.png and exits

# or run Bevy's bundled canonical example from a clone of the repo
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy && cd bevy
cargo run --example headless_renderer   # writes ./test_images/000.png

# assemble multi-frame PNGs into video
ffmpeg -framerate 30 -i out/%03d.png -pix_fmt yuv420p out/scene.mp4
```

## Failure modes
- Pin the `bevy` crate version in Cargo.toml — Bevy ships breaking API changes every ~3 months, so the headless_renderer pattern drifts between releases.
- Disable `WinitPlugin` and add `ScheduleRunnerPlugin`, or the app tries to open a window and never exits headlessly.
- First build is slow (Rust + large engine); cache the `target/` dir or builds time out.
- GPU rasterization output can vary slightly across drivers/hardware — pixel-exact reproducibility across machines is NOT guaranteed; only the Rust scene source is fully deterministic.
- The GPU→CPU copy is asynchronous: render several pre-roll frames before reading the buffer, or the saved PNG is blank/partial.
- macOS uses Metal via wgpu (no X server needed); on headless Linux ensure a working Vulkan/GL driver for wgpu.
